				\begin{document}$2.2 \times 10^{-8}~\mbox{J}\,\mbox{counts}^{-1}\,\mbox{m}^{-2}$\end{document} can be used to obtain a rough estimate of the energy content from the X123 total counts alone. A large portion of this energy (up to an order of magnitude) resides below 2 keV, and this is apparent when comparing to the corrected (divided by 0.7) GOES/XRS 0.1 – 0.8 nm flux, see Figure 10A. Figure 10
